    "probability": 0.03,
    "reasoning": "# An\u00e1lise: Carros Aut\u00f4nomos no Brasil at\u00e9 2026\n\n(a) **Time left until resolution:**\nToday is June 2, 2026. The resolution date is December 31, 2026. This leaves approximately **7 months** for autonomous vehicles to be launched in Brazil.\n\n(b) **Status quo outcome if nothing changes:**\nCurrently, there are no autonomous vehicles commercially available in Brazil. If current trajectory continues without acceleration, this situation remains unchanged through year-end 2026. The regulatory framework is still being debated (as of the 2023 articles referenced), and no major automaker has announced imminent Brazilian launches.\n\n(c) **Scenario for NO outcome:**\n- Regulatory approval processes continue at current pace (slow)\n- International autonomous vehicle companies prioritize larger markets (US, China, Europe) first\n- Technical/infrastructure challenges (road quality, signage standards, weather) delay deployment\n- Brazilian market is considered too risky or unprofitable for early-stage autonomous deployments\n- No commercial launch occurs by December 31, 2026\n\n(d) **Scenario for YES outcome:**\n- A major automaker (Tesla, Waymo, Chinese OEM, or local partner) announces and executes a commercial launch in a major Brazilian city\n- Regulatory framework is expedited through Congress\n- A pilot program counts as \"launch\" under resolution criteria\n- Technology deployment accelerates faster than typical timelines\n\n(e) **Base rate \u2014 similar events:**\n- Autonomous vehicle commercial launches globally have been extremely limited and delayed\n- Tesla's Full Self-Driving remains in beta; Waymo operates only in select US cities\n- Global rollout of autonomous vehicles has consistently lagged predictions by 3-5+ years\n- Emerging market adoption typically lags developed markets by 2-5 years\n- Technology deployments in Brazil typically face regulatory delays of 18-36 months\n- Base rate for major new automotive technology launches in Brazil within 7 months: **<5%**\n\n(f) **How current data moves from base rate:**\nThe references are from 2023, indicating regulatory discussions were ongoing then. With 18+ months elapsed to June 2026:\n- Some progress on regulatory framework is plausible\n- However, **no recent announcements about imminent Brazilian launches** are mentioned\n- Global autonomous vehicle timelines have systematically slipped\n- Tesla's timeline misses have been particularly notable\n- The short 7-month window is extremely constraining\n- **This evidence moves me DOWNWARD from base rate** - the lack of any announced near-term launch despite 18+ months of potential progress is telling\n\n(g) **Community prediction divergence:**\nNo specific community forecast is provided. However, industry consensus on autonomous vehicle timelines globally has become increasingly conservative. Most forecasters now expect limited commercial availability in Brazil before 2028-2030, not 2026.\n\n---\n\n## Reasoning Summary:\n\nThe resolution criteria requires an actual \"lan\u00e7amento de um carro com a tecnologia em territ\u00f3rio nacional\" (launch of an autonomous car in national territory) by end of 2026.\n\n**Critical factors:**\n1. **Only 7 months remain** - extremely short window\n2. **No announced launches** - absence of news is significant\n3. **Regulatory framework still in discussion** as of 2023\n4. **Global delays are norm** - autonomous vehicles systematically launch later than predicted\n5. **Brazil's regulatory environment** is typically slower than developed markets\n6. **Market prioritization** - companies launch in US, China, Europe first\n\n**What would need to happen for YES:**\n- Regulatory approval already nearly complete (no evidence of this)\n- Company commitment already made (no evidence of this)\n- Pilot/commercial launch already scheduled (no evidence of this)\n\nThe requirement for an actual deployment in just 7 months, combined with the complete absence of announced plans and ongoing regulatory work, makes this outcome highly unlikely despite autonomous vehicles existing elsewhere.\n\n**Probability: 3%**\n\nThis probability accounts for:\n- 1-2% for unexpected accelerated regulatory action + company commitment\n- 1-2% for tail risk of a major surprise announcement/pilot program I'm unaware of\n- The strong base rate against such outcomes materializing in short timeframes",
    "status": "success"
  },
  "q_29694": {
    "question_id": 29694,
    "question_text": "Will the United States disband the Department of Education through an act of Congress before 2027?",
    "probability": 0.07,
    "reasoning": "# Analysis of Department of Education Disbanding Question\n\n## (a) Time left until resolution\nThe resolution date is January 1, 2027. Today is June 2, 2026. This leaves approximately **7 months** for Congress to pass and the President to sign legislation repealing Section 201 of the Department of Education Organization Act.\n\n## (b) Status quo outcome if nothing changes\nThe Department of Education continues to operate as established in 1979. No legislative action has been taken to disband it.\n\n## (c) Scenario for NO outcome\n- Congress does not pass legislation repealing Section 201 before January 1, 2027\n- This could occur because:\n  - Competing legislative priorities consume the limited remaining months\n  - Senate Democrats (or moderate Republicans) block the legislation\n  - Procedural delays prevent passage in the compressed timeframe\n  - The incoming administration decides to deprioritize this relative to other agenda items\n  - Political feasibility concerns lead to abandonment of the effort\n\n## (d) Scenario for YES outcome\n- Congress drafts legislation repealing Section 201 of the Department of Education Organization Act\n- The legislation passes both chambers (likely with party-line or near-party-line votes)\n- The President signs it into law before January 1, 2027\n- All required legal procedures are completed\n\n## (e) Base rate \u2014 how often do similar events occur?\n\nThis is a challenging base rate question because we're asking about the elimination of a major federal department. Historical precedent:\n\n- **Cabinet departments eliminated in US history**: The Department of Commerce and Labor (1913) split into two departments; the Department of War (1949) merged into Defense. True *disbanding* without merger is extremely rare.\n- **Major agencies eliminated**: ACORN (2011), though not a department. Federal agencies are almost never completely dissolved.\n- **Legislative attempts vs. success**: Many proposals to eliminate or drastically cut departments have been made; very few pass both chambers and are signed.\n- **Base rate estimate**: Approximately 1-2% historically for actually passing legislation to eliminate a major federal department within a 7-month window.\n\n## (f) How current data/news moves you from base rate\n\n**Factors pushing toward YES:**\n- The incoming Republican administration made this an explicit campaign priority (highly unusual)\n- Republicans control Congress with majorities in both chambers (necessary condition)\n- Project 2025 represents substantial institutional planning and commitment\n- This is early in the administration's term, when political capital is highest\n- Education is sufficiently deprioritized by many constituencies that opposition might be fragmented\n\n**Factors pushing toward NO:**\n- **Time constraint is severe**: Only 7 months remain. Major legislation typically requires months of drafting, committee work, floor debate, and reconciliation\n- **Technical complexity**: Disbanding a department requires not just repealing Section 201, but addressing thousands of programs, contracts, and obligations\n- **Likely Senate obstruction**: Democrats control at minimum 51 Senate seats (with VP tiebreaker scenario unclear at current date). Even if Republican-controlled, moderate Republicans (e.g., from education-heavy states like Vermont neighbors) may defect\n- **2024 attempt precedent**: Trump administration had full control in 2017-2021 and did not successfully eliminate the Department of Education, despite similar rhetoric\n- **Resource competition**: The incoming administration has multiple priorities; Education Department elimination may lose out to tax cuts, border, or judicial appointments\n- **Public opposition**: Education is popular with suburban voters; organized opposition from states, teachers unions, and parent groups would mobilize\n- **Implementation challenges**: The practical mechanics of transferring ~2,000 programs and $200B+ in funding to states would face legal and administrative hurdles\n\n## (g) Community prediction consideration\n\nI don't have access to current community forecaster predictions on this specific question as of June 2026. However, based on the difficulty of this legislative task and historical precedent:\n- Early 2025 forecasts likely would have been 15-25% (accounting for Republican control and campaign prioritization)\n- By mid-2026, with no legislation passed, forecasts should decline significantly to 8-15%\n- The 7-month remaining window is particularly constraining\n\n## Probability Reasoning\n\nStarting from a 1-2% historical base rate for federal department elimination, I adjust upward to account for:\n1. Explicit administration prioritization (+8-10 percentage points)\n2. Republican congressional control (+6-8 percentage points)\n3. Early administration timing (+3-4 percentage points)\n\nHowever, I adjust downward substantially for:\n1. Severe time constraint: 7 months is very short for major legislation (-12-15 percentage points)\n2. No legislative progress by June 2026 despite being 5+ months into the administration (-10-12 percentage points)\n3. Likely Senate obstruction/filibuster risk (-8-10 percentage points)\n4. Historical failure to achieve this in 2017-2021 despite similar rhetoric (-5-7 percentage points)\n5. Technical complexity of implementation (-3-5 percentage points)\n\nThe critical observation is that by June 2026, if this were a genuine priority with achievable legislative pathway, we would expect to see significant progress: drafted bills in committee, floor scheduling, public administration positioning. The absence of such signals suggests either the priority has been deprioritized or the administration has concluded it's not legislatively feasible.\n\n**Probability: 7%**",
    "status": "success"
  },
  "q_35850": {
    "question_id": 35850,
    "question_text": "Will minimum staffing standards for Long-Term Care Facilities of 3.48 hours per resident per day be in effect before May 11, 2027?",
    "probability": 0.78,
    "reasoning": "I'll work through this systematically.\n\n## (a) Time left until resolution\nFrom today (June 2, 2026) to May 11, 2027 = approximately 11 months remaining.\n\n## (b) Status quo outcome if nothing changes\nThe rule was published June 21, 2024, with a May 10, 2027 implementation deadline. If nothing changes, the rule goes into effect as scheduled on May 10, 2027 - meaning the answer would be YES.\n\n## (c) Scenario for NO outcome\nThe rule is blocked or rolled back before May 11, 2027 through:\n1. **Congressional action**: Republicans pass legislation repealing/defunding the rule (budget reconciliation, appropriations riders, or direct repeal)\n2. **Court action**: Federal courts overturn the rule as exceeding CMS authority or on other grounds\n3. **Administrative action**: CMS under Trump reverses or delays implementation\n4. **Effective delay**: Rule is technically in effect but implementation is delayed past May 11, 2027\n\n## (d) Scenario for YES outcome\nThe rule remains in effect and is implemented on or before May 10, 2027. Most non-rural Medicare/Medicaid LTC facilities must comply with the 3.48 hours per resident per day standard by the deadline.\n\n## (e) Base rate \u2014 how often do similar events occur?\nHistorical context on healthcare rules:\n- Most final CMS rules do proceed to implementation as scheduled (~70-75% of major rules)\n- However, Trump administration has shown willingness to reverse/delay Obama/Biden-era healthcare rules (ACA challenges, various HHS rollbacks)\n- Congressional repeal of healthcare regulations is moderately successful when one party controls both chambers (~40-50% success rate when pursued)\n- Court challenges to CMS rules have mixed success; majority are upheld (~60-70%)\n\nFor a rule with significant industry opposition, bipartisan political concerns, and an incoming administration with demonstrated willingness to roll back prior rules, base rate for implementation would be lower than the ~70-75% baseline - perhaps 50-55%.\n\n## (f) How current data/news moves me from base rate\n\n**Key developments since the rule was published:**\n\n1. **Trump DOJ defense (April 3, 2025)**: This is VERY significant. Trump's own Department of Justice filed a strong defense of the rule in court. This suggests Trump administration support is real, not just tactical.\n\n2. **Status as of June 2, 2026**: We're now only 11 months from implementation. At this point:\n   - No successful Congressional repeal has occurred despite Republican control of Congress\n   - No court has overturned the rule\n   - Trump administration has not reversed it\n\n3. **Industry pressure remains**: The healthcare industry is strongly opposed and has significant lobbying power, but lack of Congressional action despite ~21 months of opportunity suggests the political will to block it may be weaker than expected.\n\n4. **Timeline implications**: With only 11 months remaining, any new Congressional action would need to pass quickly. Budget reconciliation windows are limited, and other legislative priorities may take precedence.\n\n5. **Implementation readiness**: Facilities have had nearly 2 years to prepare. Many have likely begun hiring and restructuring.\n\nThe Trump DOJ's defense in April 2025 is the most consequential recent data point. It directly contradicts the assumption that Trump would roll back the rule. This moves the probability significantly upward from the base rate.\n\n## (g) Community prediction check\n\nI don't have access to current community predictions on this specific question, but based on the resolution criteria and evidence:\n- The rule has survived 21 months without being repealed or overturned\n- Trump administration has actively defended it in court\n- Implementation is now 11 months away with no blocking mechanism currently in place\n- Industry opposition exists but hasn't prevented progress\n\nThese factors strongly support implementation.\n\n## Reasoning Summary\n\n**In favor of YES (Rule Takes Effect):**\n- Trump DOJ actively defending the rule (strong signal)\n- No Congressional repeal despite 21+ months and Republican control\n- No court has overturned it\n- Rule is scheduled and timeline is imminent\n- Facilities have had time to prepare\n\n**In favor of NO (Rule Blocked):**\n- Significant healthcare industry opposition\n- Some Republican opposition remains\n- Could theoretically be delayed by new litigation\n- Administrative delays remain possible (though unlikely given Trump DOJ support)\n\nThe Trump DOJ's defense filing in April 2025 is the decisive factor. This represents clear executive branch commitment to the rule under the current administration. With only 11 months remaining and no blocking action successfully implemented despite over 21 months of opportunity, the probability the rule takes effect has increased substantially.\n\nThe main remaining risks are: (1) unexpected Congressional action in the next 11 months, (2) a court filing a late injunction, or (3) a dramatic policy reversal by the Trump administration. Each of these is now relatively unlikely given the track record.\n\n**Probability: 78%**",
    "status": "success"
  },
  "q_35205": {
    "question_id": 35205,
    "question_text": "Will the Democrats control the House of Representatives at any point before Jan 3, 2027?",
    "probability": 0.22,
    "reasoning": "# Analysis: Will Democrats Control the House Before Jan 3, 2027?\n\n## (a) Time Left Until Resolution\n- Current date: June 2, 2026\n- Resolution date: January 3, 2027\n- **Time remaining: ~7 months**\n\n## (b) Status Quo Outcome If Nothing Changes\nRepublicans maintain their 218-215 majority (with 2 vacant seats). Without any deaths, resignations, or special elections, control remains Republican through January 3, 2027. The status quo slightly favors NO.\n\n## (c) Scenario for NO Outcome\n- Republicans hold their narrow majority through the remainder of 2026\n- No significant seat changes occur before January 3, 2027\n- Even after November 2026 elections, Republicans win enough seats to maintain control\n- This is the baseline expectation given current partisan lean and redistricting\n\n## (d) Scenario for YES Outcome\nFor Democrats to control the House before Jan 3, 2027, one of these must occur:\n\n1. **Deaths/Resignations Path**: 4+ Republican seats flip to Democratic control through vacancies and special elections (net gain of 4 seats gives Democrats 219 assuming 220 total seats)\n\n2. **Special Election Path**: A string of special elections in Republican districts result in Democratic pickups (historically rare in same-party-held seats)\n\n3. **Defection Path**: Republican members switch parties or change caucusing affiliation (extremely rare in modern era)\n\n4. **November 2026 Election Path**: Democrats win a net gain of 4+ seats in the general election (possible but Republicans have structural advantages including redistricting)\n\n## (e) Base Rate \u2014 How Often Do Similar Events Occur?\n\n**Historical precedent from the prompt**: The 72nd Congress (1931-1933) did see control switch from 217-216 R to 220-206 D. This occurred due to a combination of special elections and seat changes mid-Congress. This is the only modern precedent explicitly cited.\n\n**General base rates**:\n- Mid-Congress control shifts are rare in the modern era (last occurred in 2009 with the 111th Congress starting)\n- With a margin of only 3 seats (218-215), Republicans are vulnerable\n- Historical 72nd Congress example shows it CAN happen with similarly narrow margins\n- Special election performance typically favors opposition party, but margins are usually small\n- Attrition (deaths, resignations) occurs but unpredictably\n\n**Rough base rate estimate for a 3-seat majority flipping in one Congress**: ~15-25% historically when margins are this tight\n\n## (f) How Current Data/News Moves Me From Base Rate\n\n**Factors pushing toward YES**:\n- Republicans have the narrowest majority in nearly 100 years (as stated)\n- Historical precedent exists (72nd Congress) with similar margin that flipped\n- 7 months is a meaningful timeframe for deaths, resignations, special elections\n- Typical congressional attrition rate: ~5-10 seats per Congress through natural causes/resignations\n- Trump-related legal jeopardy and distractions may increase Republican retirements\n- Special elections in 2023-2024 showed Democrats outperforming in traditionally Republican areas\n\n**Factors pushing toward NO**:\n- Republicans have demonstrated ability to maintain discipline in recent years\n- The November 2026 election still favors Republicans due to redistricting and presidential election off-year dynamics\n- Democrats gaining 4+ seats through special elections/attrition alone is a high bar\n- We're only 7 months out; most congressional deaths/resignations are unpredictable but historically distributed across the full 2-year term\n- Special elections: only need to look at a subset of potential vacancies, and Republicans would likely hold most of their seats in special elections\n\n**Adjusting from base rate**: The explicit historical precedent (72nd Congress with similar margins) is the strongest evidence. However, that was nearly 100 years ago in a different era with different political dynamics. The 3-seat margin is genuinely thin and increases vulnerability. The timeframe is 7 months, which is substantial but less than a full Congress.\n\n**Net adjustment**: Base rate of ~20% moves slightly upward to account for the thin margin and historical precedent, but tempered by the fact that November 2026 election is unlikely to deliver gains for Democrats given electoral fundamentals.\n\n## (g) Community Prediction Comparison\n\nI don't have access to current community forecasts for this specific question. If forecasts exist significantly above or below my estimate, I would consider:\n- Whether they're heavily weighting the November 2026 election (where fundamentals favor Republicans)\n- Whether they're appropriately accounting for the extremely high bar of 4+ net seat changes in 7 months\n- Whether they're overweighting the historical precedent vs. modern political dynamics\n\n---\n\n## Reasoning Summary\n\nThe core question hinges on whether 4+ Republican seats flip to Democratic control in the next 7 months through:\n1. Deaths/resignations creating special elections (unpredictable, but odds of 4+ in 7 months are modest)\n2. Republicans losing those special elections (possible but not typical for same-party-held seats)\n3. Defections (extremely unlikely in modern era)\n4. November 2026 elections delivering significant gains (unlikely given off-year dynamics and redistricting)\n\nThe 72nd Congress precedent (1931-1933) shows it's possible with thin margins, but that was under very different political and procedural circumstances. Modern Congress has higher party discipline.\n\nThe 3-seat Republican margin is genuinely precarious and increases baseline vulnerability compared to typical majorities. However, the burden of 4+ net seat changes in 7 months is high.\n\n**Probability: 22%**",
    "status": "success"
  },
  "q_40792": {
