    "question_text": "Will Saudi Arabia and Israel agree to normalise diplomatic relations during 2026?",
    "probability": 0.22,
    "reasoning": "# Saudi-Israel Normalization Analysis\n\n## (a) Time left until resolution\nApproximately **7 months** remain until January 1, 2027. This is a relatively short timeframe for diplomatic breakthroughs of this magnitude.\n\n## (b) Status quo outcome if nothing changes\nIf current dynamics persist, no normalization agreement would be announced. The Israel-Gaza conflict continues with substantial humanitarian consequences, which has hardened Saudi Arabia's public position. The status quo involves:\n- Continued Israeli military operations in Gaza\n- Saudi Arabia maintaining rhetorical support for Palestinian cause\n- No active normalization talks being publicly discussed\n- Periodic but contained Israeli-Iranian tensions\n\n## (c) Scenario for NO outcome\n- The Gaza conflict continues through 2026 without resolution, making any Saudi-Israeli deal politically costly for the Saudi leadership\n- Palestinian casualties and international pressure make normalization unpalatable domestically in Saudi Arabia\n- Iran continues to exert diplomatic pressure on Riyadh to avoid alignment with Israel\n- Regional dynamics remain tense, making backroom diplomacy impossible\n- No significant shift in American pressure or incentives for normalization\n- The question reaches January 1, 2027 without an announced agreement\n\n## (d) Scenario for YES outcome\n- A ceasefire or significant de-escalation occurs in Gaza over the next 6 months, reducing international pressure on Saudi Arabia\n- The Trump administration (or successor) intensifies diplomatic pressure on both parties as part of broader Middle East realignment\n- Saudi Arabia and Israel recognize mutual benefits around Iran containment, regional stability, and economic cooperation\n- A back-channel negotiation matures into a formal announcement before year-end\n- The agreement is framed as \"conditional\" on Palestinian progress, allowing Saudi Arabia to save face domestically\n- Both parties see sufficient strategic alignment that domestic political costs become manageable\n\n## (e) Base rate \u2014 similar events\nHistorical precedent for Arab-Israeli normalization:\n- **UAE-Bahrain (2020)**: Two smaller, less historically opposed states normalized after US pressure\n- **Egypt-Israel (1979)**: Took 30 years of conflict; required US mediation and incentives\n- **Jordan-Israel (1994)**: Took 46 years; required direct negotiations after initial secret talks\n- **Morocco-Israel (2020)**: Normalized without deep historical enmity comparable to Saudi Arabia\n- **Saudi Arabia specifically**: Never normalized despite decades of improving relations; highest stakes due to guardianship of holy sites and Palestinian cause\n\nThe base rate for major Arab nations normalizing with Israel within a 7-month window is **extremely low** \u2014 perhaps 5-10% when considering the political costs and typical diplomatic timeline. Saudi Arabia is higher stakes than UAE/Bahrain due to its regional weight and religious role.\n\n## (f) How current data/news moves me from base rate\n\n**Factors moving toward YES (increasing probability):**\n- The Trump administration returned to power in January 2025 with expressed interest in Middle East deals\n- Saudi Arabia has shown willingness to normalize (pre-Gaza escalation in 2023 discussions)\n- Both countries have mutual Iran containment interests\n- The question only requires an *announcement*, not implementation \u2014 lower bar\n\n**Factors moving toward NO (decreasing probability):**\n- We are already in June 2026 with no public normalization talks announced or underway\n- The Gaza conflict is still ongoing (as of June 2026) with no resolution in sight\n- Saudi Arabia has publicly hardened its position since October 2023\n- Only 7 months remain \u2014 insufficient time for typical diplomatic processes unless advanced talks are already happening in secret\n- No recent credible reporting of active normalization negotiations\n- The political cost to Saudi Arabia of normalizing while Gaza conflict continues is extremely high domestically and regionally\n\nThe critical question is whether secret talks have already advanced to the stage where an announcement is possible in the next 7 months. Current lack of public indication suggests this is unlikely.\n\n## (g) Community prediction divergence\nI don't have access to current Metaculus or similar forecasting community predictions on this specific question. However, if the community prediction is materially above 25%, I would diverge downward because:\n- The base rate for Saudi normalization specifically is much lower than for other Arab nations\n- We are already at June 2026 with no credible indications of active talks\n- The timing is extremely compressed for such a significant geopolitical shift\n- Recent Saudi rhetoric remains hardened on the Palestinian cause\n\nIf the community is below 15%, I would likely be in the same ballpark or moderately higher, accounting for the possibility of advanced secret diplomacy.\n\n---\n\n## Probability: 22%\n\n**Reasoning Summary:** While Saudi Arabia has demonstrated capacity for normalization (pre-2023), the current trajectory makes announcement in the next 7 months unlikely. The base rate for major Arab-Israeli normalization within short timeframes is very low. However, I'm not going lower than 15% because: (1) the Trump administration's explicit interest creates genuine pressure, (2) \"conditional\" agreements are easier to announce, and (3) there's a non-trivial probability of advanced secret talks. The 7-month window is very tight but not impossible if diplomacy has already substantially progressed. The lack of public indication at this point (June 2026) is the strongest evidence against YES, pushing me below 25%, but not to single digits given the possibility of surprise announcements in geopolitics.",
    "status": "success"
  },
  "q_40303": {
