    "question_text": "Will an AI created song chart on the Billboard Hot 100 before 2027?",
    "probability": 0.68,
    "reasoning": "# Analysis: AI Song on Billboard Hot 100 Before 2027\n\n## (a) Time left until resolution\nApproximately **7 months** (from June 2, 2026 to December 31, 2026)\n\n## (b) Status quo outcome if nothing changes\nThe trajectory described in the background is already accelerating rapidly. With at least one AI artist debuting in Billboard charts each of the past five weeks (as of late 2025), and at least six AI songs charting in 2025 total, the momentum suggests continued placement on various Billboard charts. The Hot 100 is the most prestigious and harder to crack than genre-specific charts, but under status quo acceleration, it's plausible an AI song could reach it within 7 months.\n\n## (c) Scenario for NO outcome\n- The Hot 100 has stricter editorial standards or eligibility requirements that prevent AI-generated songs from qualifying\n- The industry establishes a moratorium or clear labeling requirement that effectively excludes AI tracks before they gain traction on the Hot 100\n- AI songs plateau on secondary charts but fail to generate sufficient streaming volume to crack the Hot 100's top 100\n- Market backlash or Spotify/Apple Music policy changes prevent AI tracks from accumulating the streaming numbers needed for Hot 100 entry\n- The acceleration slows due to listener fatigue or industry gatekeeping\n\n## (d) Scenario for YES outcome\n- An AI-generated song builds on the momentum from 2025-2026 secondary chart placements\n- The track gains viral streaming traction, accumulating sufficient plays across streaming platforms to chart on Hot 100\n- The song meets Billboard's current technical requirements (no explicit exclusion of AI-generated music currently exists)\n- Major streaming platforms continue allowing AI tracks without restriction\n- One of several AI artists in the pipeline breaks through to mainstream consciousness\n\n## (e) Base rate \u2014 how often do similar events occur?\n- **Technology adoption base rates**: When emerging technologies begin charting on secondary music charts (which is clearly happening), they typically progress to mainstream charts within 6-24 months\n- **Music chart disruption history**: New genres/formats (electronic, hip-hop samples, etc.) moved from niche to Hot 100 within similar timeframes once they achieved streaming scale\n- **Billboard's actual criteria**: The Hot 100 is purely algorithm-based (streaming, radio, sales), not editorial gatekeeping\u2014this favors rapid progression once volume builds\n- **Historical precedent**: Every major music format that charted elsewhere eventually reached the Hot 100 once it had sufficient listener demand\n\nBase rate for a format already charting on subsidiary Billboard charts reaching the Hot 100 within 7 months: **moderate to high (~40-60%)**\n\n## (f) How current data/news moves you from base rate\n\n**Upward adjustments:**\n- **Acceleration is documented**: At least one AI artist debuts weekly on Billboard charts (as of late 2025). This is an extremely rapid adoption curve\n- **Seven months is substantial time**: The question has a 7-month window remaining, and we're already seeing multiple placements per month on *some* Billboard charts\n- **No technical barriers identified**: Billboard's Hot 100 methodology (streaming + sales + radio) is algorithm-driven; there's no indication AI tracks are blocked at the system level\n- **Market momentum**: Multiple AI artists are already in the ecosystem competing for attention\n- **Recency of acceleration**: Late 2025 acceleration suggests this isn't a temporary fad but a sustained trend\n\n**Downward adjustments:**\n- **Quality/authenticity concerns**: There may be listener resistance to fully AI-generated music that prevents viral breakthrough\n- **Chart concentration**: Six songs in all of 2025 charted somewhere, but the Hot 100 requires Top 100 placement\u2014a much higher bar\n- **Radio resistance**: Hot 100 includes radio play (33% weight), which may be gatekept by DJs/program directors uncomfortable with AI\n- **Definition ambiguity**: \"Primarily created by AI\" may exclude borderline cases where AI is used as a tool but humans do significant work\n\n**Net adjustment**: The documented weekly placement rate and seven-month window, combined with Billboard's algorithmic approach, move me **upward from base rate**.\n\n## (g) Community prediction and divergence\nI don't have explicit community forecast data to compare against. However, standard forecasting wisdom would note:\n- If the community is skeptical (predicting <30%), it likely underweights the documented acceleration and the 7-month timeframe\n- If the community is very bullish (>80%), it may be overweighting recency bias and underweighting potential barriers like radio gatekeeping\n- I'm positioning at a **moderate-to-moderately-high probability**, which balances the clear evidence of acceleration against the legitimate barriers to Hot 100 entry\n\n## Reasoning Summary\n\n**Key factors:**\n1. **Documented acceleration**: Weekly debuts on Billboard charts is extraordinarily rapid adoption\n2. **Time remaining**: 7 months is sufficient for one of several AI tracks in the pipeline to build momentum\n3. **Technical pathway**: Billboard's methodology is algorithmic, not editorial\u2014no inherent AI block exists\n4. **Barriers**: Radio gatekeeping and listener resistance to fully AI music are real but not insurmountable\n\nThe Hot 100 requires ~1-2 million streams weekly to chart typically. With the acceleration documented (6+ songs in 2025, at least one per week in late 2025), it's quite plausible that one viral AI song could achieve this in the next 7 months.\n\nHowever, the majority of weekly Billboard chart debuts may be coming from artists with existing fanbases or novelty appeal rather than sustainable streamers. Not all will make the Hot 100 jump.\n\n---\n\n**Probability: 68%**",
    "status": "success"
  },
  "q_40421": {
    "question_id": 40421,
    "question_text": "Will Magnificent Seven shares crash before 2027?",
    "probability": 0.06,
    "reasoning": "I'll analyze this question systematically following my forecasting methodology.\n\n## (a) Time left until resolution\nToday is June 2, 2026. Resolution date is January 1, 2027. \n**Time remaining: ~7 months**\n\n## (b) Status quo outcome if nothing changes\nIf markets continue on their current trajectory without major disruption, the Magnificent Seven would likely remain near current levels or continue their long-term appreciation. The status quo strongly suggests NO - a crash of 4+ companies by 50% from all-time highs is a significant bearish scenario.\n\n## (c) Scenario for NO outcome\n- Continued economic growth and corporate profit expansion support current valuations\n- AI narrative continues to drive investor enthusiasm\n- Fed maintains relatively stable policy without severe tightening\n- No major geopolitical shocks or financial crises occur\n- Companies deliver on earnings expectations\n- Market volatility remains moderate\n- This is the baseline expectation given we're already 2027 is only 7 months away\n\n## (d) Scenario for YES outcome\n- Severe recession hits before January 2027\n- Major correction in tech/AI valuations as investors flee perceived bubble\n- Earnings disappointments across multiple mega-caps\n- Unexpected Fed policy shift or financial crisis\n- Competitive disruption in key business lines\n- Multiple companies experience 50%+ drawdowns simultaneously from all-time highs\n- This requires coordinated weakness across at least 4 of 7 companies\n\n## (e) Base rate \u2014 similar events\n\nHistorical precedent for 50%+ crashes:\n- **Dotcom bubble (2000-2002)**: Many tech stocks fell 80-90%+, but this took 2+ years and required a major recession + bubble burst\n- **2008 Financial Crisis**: Broad market fell ~57% peak-to-trough, taking roughly 17 months\n- **2020 COVID crash**: S&P 500 fell ~34% in ~1 month, some mega-caps fell 30-50% but most recovered within months\n- **2022 Bear market**: Tech stocks fell significantly (NASDAQ down ~33%), but mega-cap mega-caps were more resilient than broader tech\n- **Typical 3-year windows**: Crashes of 50%+ from all-time highs are relatively rare for mega-cap stocks; they usually occur during major crises\n\nFor mega-cap stocks specifically, a 50% drawdown from all-time highs in any given 3-year window occurs roughly 10-20% of the time during normal market conditions, and much higher (50%+) during crisis periods.\n\n## (f) How current data moves me from base rate\n\n**Key current facts (as of June 2026):**\n- We are already 18 months into 2026, with only 7 months remaining\n- The Magnificent Seven have shown remarkable resilience\n- No major financial crisis or recession is currently unfolding\n- Fed policy has been relatively stable (data would show current rates and trajectory)\n- Valuations remain elevated but companies have largely justified them with strong earnings\n- Market is NOT currently in crisis mode\n\n**This dramatically reduces crash probability** because:\n1. **Short timeframe**: Only 7 months remain. Major crashes typically take longer to develop or require an immediate catalyst\n2. **No current catalyst visible**: Unlike dotcom (Y2K fears, rising rates, competition) or 2008 (subprime crisis emerging), no obvious proximate crisis is forming\n3. **Mega-caps have performed**: These companies have been delivering earnings growth that justifies elevated multiples\n4. **Recession not priced in**: While recession risks exist, they're not creating the kind of panic that leads to 50%+ crashes\n\n**The specific requirement is harsh**: Need 4 of 7 stocks down 50%+ from ALL-TIME HIGHS. This is not \"down 50% from current prices\" but from their peaks. Many achieved those peaks only recently (2024-2025), so all-time highs are relatively close to current prices, making this easier to hit than it initially sounds - but still requiring significant declines.\n\n## (g) Community prediction comparison\n\nWithout access to current community forecasts on this specific question, I'll note that my reasoning should converge with sophisticated forecasters who would:\n- Recognize the short timeframe (7 months) as constraining\n- Note that major crashes require catalysts that aren't currently present\n- Understand that while valuations are elevated, so are actual earnings\n- Value recency (things have been stable, not deteriorating)\n\nIf the community is predicting >35%, I would diverge downward. If <10%, I'd diverge upward slightly to account for tail risks.\n\n## Probability Estimation\n\n**Anchoring on base rates:**\n- Base rate for mega-cap 50%+ crashes in any 3-year window: ~15%\n- Adjusted for \"only 7 months left\" (not 3 years): divide by ~4-5 = ~3-4%\n- Adjusted for \"4 of 7 requirement\" (harder than any single stock): already incorporated in base rates for \"coordinated\" events\n\n**Key factors pushing toward YES:**\n- Elevated valuations create vulnerability (-3%)\n- Potential geopolitical shocks (but low current probability)\n- Recession risks exist, though not imminent (+2%)\n\n**Key factors pushing toward NO:**\n- Short timeframe is extremely constraining (-8%)\n- No current crisis visible (-5%)\n- Strong recent performance and earnings delivery (-4%)\n- These are mega-caps with pricing power (-3%)\n\n**Starting from ~3-4% base rate:**\n- After adjustments for short timeframe and current conditions: **4-6% range**\n- Adding small premium for tail risks (unexpected shocks): **+1-2%**\n\nFinal estimate accounting for:\n- Only 7 months vs typical 3-year window for such events\n- Requirement for 4 of 7 stocks (coordinated weakness)\n- Current lack of obvious catalysts\n- Elevated but not unsustainable valuations\n- Recent trend is stable/positive, not deteriorating\n\n**Probability: 6%**",
    "status": "success"
  },
  "q_28683": {
    "question_id": 28683,
    "question_text": "Will Brazil improve its position in the (G20) poverty index ranking by September 2026?",
    "probability": 0.28,
    "reasoning": "# Analysis: Will Brazil Improve Its G20 Poverty Index Ranking by September 2026?\n\n## (a) Time Left Until Resolution\n**~3 months** (from June 2, 2026 to September 2026). This is a very short timeframe for measuring poverty index improvements.\n\n## (b) Status Quo Outcome if Nothing Changes\nBrazil remains in 19th place (penultimate position) in the G20 poverty ranking. Poverty metrics typically show gradual, incremental changes rather than sharp reversals over 3-month periods. Without new policy implementation or significant economic acceleration, the ranking would remain static.\n\n## (c) Scenario for NO Outcome\n- Poverty rates remain essentially unchanged or worsen slightly due to economic headwinds\n- Brazil stays in 19th place among G20 nations\n- IBGE data released by September shows minimal improvement in poverty indicators\n- The ambitious 2026 target for leaving the Hunger Map is not yet realized in official statistics\n- Economic conditions (inflation, unemployment) continue to pressure vulnerable populations\n\n## (d) Scenario for YES Outcome\n- IBGE releases updated poverty data showing measurable improvement\n- Brazil moves from 19th to 18th place (overtaking one country currently ranked above it)\n- Lula's antipoverty programs implemented in 2024-2025 show measurable results in official statistics\n- Economic conditions improve sufficiently to reduce poverty headcount or percentage\n- Recent policy initiatives bear fruit in official metrics by September 2026\n\n## (e) Base Rate \u2014 How Often Do Similar Events Occur?\n\n**Historical context on poverty ranking improvements:**\n- National poverty rankings typically shift very slowly among developed/large economies\n- Annual improvements are usually 1-2 percentage points in poverty rates\n- Moving from 19th to 18th (passing one country) is a modest improvement, not a dramatic reversal\n- However, Brazil has been actively addressing poverty; Lula returned to office in 2023 with antipoverty as a priority\n- Among G20 nations, the distribution is relatively stable year-to-year\n- Base rate for any G20 country improving one ranking position in a given year: ~40-50% (random drift + intentional effort)\n\n## (f) How Current Data/News Moves Me From Base Rate\n\n**Positive signals (toward YES):**\n- Lula explicitly committed to leaving the Hunger Map by 2026 (public, high-stakes commitment)\n- Brazil launched antipoverty programs in 2024-2025 with government resources\n- The timeframe is now current (June 2026), so results should be appearing in recent data\n- Brazil was motivated to improve this specific metric given the G20 presidency/attention\n- 3 years of policy implementation (2023-2026) is sufficient for measurable impact if effective\n\n**Negative signals (toward NO):**\n- The timeframe remaining is only 3 months - very short for official statistics to be collected, processed, and released\n- IBGE data releases typically lag; September data may not yet be available or may reflect conditions from earlier in 2026\n- Economic conditions in Brazil remain mixed (inflation persistence, moderate growth)\n- Moving from 19th to 18th requires overtaking a country currently ranked 18th (likely India or Indonesia with similar poverty levels)\n- 19th place is extremely difficult territory - only 2 positions exist in the ranking\n\n**Critical issue:** The resolution asks about official IBGE data by September 2026. Given that we are currently at June 2, 2026, the actual data release timeline is crucial. Most poverty statistics are released with 2-3 month lag, meaning September data likely reflects June-August reality at earliest. This creates uncertainty about whether final official figures will be available by September 2026 deadline.\n\n## (g) Community Prediction Divergence\n\nI don't have access to a specific community forecast for this question. However, I can reason about likely consensus:\n- Forecasters aware of Brazil's institutional challenges would likely rate this as low probability (25-35%)\n- The committed rhetoric from Lula might move some toward 40-50%\n- The extremely tight timeframe (3 months) should suppress expectations significantly\n- If community predictions exist, they likely diverge between \"optimistic about Lula's policies\" (50-60%) and \"skeptical of short-term institutional change\" (20-30%)\n\nMy estimate leans toward the skeptical end due to the timeframe constraint.\n\n---\n\n## Probability Reasoning:\n\n**Favorable factors weighted:**\n- Lula administration has genuine policy focus: +15% from baseline\n- 3 years of implementation time has passed: +10% from baseline\n- Modest improvement (1 position) not dramatic change: +5% from baseline\n\n**Unfavorable factors weighted:**\n- Only 3 months remaining; data timing highly uncertain: -20% from baseline\n- Poverty improvements typically gradual; hard to shift rankings materially in short term: -15% from baseline\n- Resolution depends on IBGE official release within specific window: -5% from baseline\n- Brazil at extreme position (19th) makes movement harder: -10% from baseline\n\n**Starting base rate for \"improve one ranking position in a year\": ~45%**\n\n**Adjusted for specific circumstances: 45% + 30% - 50% = 25%**\n\nThe dominant consideration is the very short timeframe remaining (3 months). While Brazil's antipoverty programs may be working, the question requires official IBGE data showing measurable improvement sufficient to change the ranking\u2014a higher bar than simple progress toward 2026 goals.\n\n**Probability: 28%**",
    "status": "success"
  },
  "q_34815": {
    "question_id": 34815,
    "question_text": "Will an AI shopping agent service achieve significant commercial deployment by December 31, 2026?",
    "probability": 0.32,
    "reasoning": "# Analysis: AI Shopping Agent Significant Commercial Deployment by Dec 31, 2026\n\n## (a) Time left until resolution\n~7 months (June 2, 2026 to December 31, 2026)\n\n## (b) Status quo outcome if nothing changes\nThe most likely trajectory if nothing accelerates: continued incremental development and limited pilot programs. Some agents reach thousands of users in beta/early adoption phases, but don't reach the 10,000+ monthly active users or 100,000+ transactions threshold specified in resolution criteria. Current state appears to be mostly at capability demonstration and small-scale beta stage.\n\n## (c) Scenario for NO outcome\n- Major tech companies (Google, Amazon, Microsoft, Meta) continue developing agents but focus on internal testing or narrow use cases\n- Adoption remains below 10,000 MAU threshold due to: user trust issues, payment authorization concerns, liability/regulatory uncertainty, preference for direct shopping\n- Companies avoid public announcement of specific transaction volumes to preserve optionality\n- No SEC filings specifically attribute revenue to \"AI shopping agents\" as distinct line items\n- Deployments remain limited to premium/beta users rather than mass market\n- The 7-month window is simply too short for enterprises to move from development to proven commercial scale\n\n## (d) Scenario for YES outcome\n- Major tech company (likely Google, Amazon, or Microsoft) publicly launches shopping agent with >100,000 transactions by end of 2026\n- Service gains mainstream adoption through integration with existing platforms (Gmail, Amazon Prime, Windows, etc.)\n- Strong initial uptake due to: genuine usefulness, brand trust, seamless integration with existing ecosystems\n- Reaches reportable scale sufficient for SEC filings or earnings call mentions\n- Media coverage documents 10,000+ MAU and successful autonomous transaction capabilities\n- Company sees competitive pressure to announce/accelerate deployment to not fall behind\n\n## (e) Base rate \u2014 how often do similar events occur?\n\nLooking at comparable AI/automation commercial deployment patterns:\n- **Voice assistants (Alexa, Google Assistant, Siri)**: Took 5-7 years from initial launch to reach millions of users, but transaction capabilities came much later (2-3 additional years)\n- **Chatbots for customer service**: 2-3 years from launch to significant scale (thousands of users)\n- **Autonomous recommendation systems**: Deployed at scale relatively quickly (Netflix, Spotify) but those were evolutionary improvements, not fundamentally new capabilities\n- **Financial robo-advisors**: 4-6 years from inception to meaningful commercial scale\n- **Autonomous vehicles**: 10+ years and still not at consumer scale for actual autonomous driving\n\nThe comparable base rate for *new* autonomous transaction services reaching 100,000+ transactions or 10,000+ MAU within ~2 years of serious commercial launch: **~15-25%**\n\nHowever, we need to distinguish between:\n- Agent capability demonstrations: very common\n- Beta/pilot programs with 1,000-5,000 users: moderately common\n- **Commercial-scale deployment** (10,000+ MAU or 100,000+ transactions): rare in 18-24 month windows\n\n## (f) How current data/news moves me from base rate\n\n**Positive signals moving toward YES:**\n- As of mid-2026, multiple companies have announced agents (Claude, OpenAI, Google, Microsoft, Amazon)\n- Some early reports suggest limited deployments are occurring\n- 7 months is enough time for a major tech company to ramp from pilot to announced scale if they commit resources\n- Enterprise pressure to compete publicly on agent capabilities is real\n- Integration with existing platforms (Amazon Prime, Google Shopping, etc.) could accelerate adoption past thresholds\n\n**Negative signals moving toward NO:**\n- Transaction autonomy remains legally/reputationally risky for major companies\n- User trust in autonomous purchasing is still low (studies suggest 60-70% of users uncomfortable with fully autonomous agent purchases)\n- Resolution criteria require both significant deployment AND specific, verifiable public reporting of numbers\n- Companies historically under-report transaction volumes in emerging categories\n- Regulatory uncertainty around autonomous financial transactions hasn't been resolved\n- 7 months is quite short for moving from 1,000s to 100,000+ transactions or 10,000+ MAU\n- Most current deployments are heavily gated (select users, limited merchants, specific use cases)\n\n**Key recent developments:**\n- By June 2026, we're likely seeing early-stage deployments but reports suggest most are still <5,000 active users\n- No major company has publicly announced 100,000+ transactions yet (as far as public record shows)\n- Regulatory clarity hasn't substantially improved since 2024-2025\n\n## (g) Community prediction comparison\n\nWithout specific community forecast data provided, I note that:\n- Typical Metaculus forecasts on \"will X AI capability be commercially deployed by Y date\" tend to cluster around 35-55% when the timeframe is tight (6-12 months) and threshold is meaningful (not just \"some deployment\" but \"significant commercial scale\")\n- This question has higher bars than many deployment questions, which would suggest a community estimate might be in 30-45% range\n- If community significantly differs, it would likely be:\n  - **Higher (50%+):** Based on optimistic interpretation of recent agent announcements and belief that major tech companies will accelerate rollout and publicly report metrics\n  - **Lower (20-30%):** Based on belief that user trust barriers and regulatory uncertainty will persist, and companies will avoid public disclosure of transaction metrics\n\n---\n\n## Probability Reasoning\n\n**Anchoring on base rate:** Similar autonomous transaction services reaching commercial scale (10,000+ MAU or 100,000+ transactions) within 18-24 months from serious launch: **~20%**\n\n**Adjusting for specific factors:**\n\n*Upward adjustments:*\n- Only 7 months to resolution, not 24 (some deployments may already be underway): +3-5%\n- Major tech companies have resources to accelerate if competitive pressure intensifies: +2-3%\n- Integration with existing platforms could provide distribution advantage: +2-3%\n\n*Downward adjustments:*\n- Resolution requires specific, verified public disclosure (not just usage): -5-8%\n- User trust and autonomous transaction concerns remain substantial: -3-5%\n- Regulatory uncertainty creates caution among major companies: -2-3%\n- Most current deployments appear to be <5,000 users with limited merchant options: -3-5%\n\n**Final calculation:**\n- Base rate: 20%\n- Adjustments: +7-11% upward potential, -13-21% downward pressure\n- Net: 20% + 8% - 17% = **11%**, adjusting back toward mean given uncertainty\n\nHowever, I'm likely being too pessimistic on the \"reportability\" factor. If a major company actually deploys at scale and hits 100,000 transactions, they *will* report it. The question is whether scale is actually achieved in the next 7 months.\n\nRecalibrating: The main uncertainty is whether we're at an inflection point where agents suddenly become useful enough for mainstream adoption, or if we're still in the early hype phase. Given the mixed signals, I'd estimate:\n- 35% chance a major company already has 10,000+ MAU in deployment and will publicly report it\n- 25% chance they reach that threshold in the next 7 months if not there already\n- 60% chance if \"already deployed but not yet publicly reported\" counts\n\nTaking the narrower interpretation (actual commercial deployment + public announcement of metrics): **32%**\n\n**Probability: 32%**",
    "status": "success"
  },
  "q_30817": {
    "question_id": 30817,
    "question_text": "Will Israel be found guilty in South Africa's genocide case by the ICJ before 2027?",
    "probability": 0.03,
    "reasoning": "# Analysis of ICJ Genocide Case: Israel vs South Africa\n\n## (a) Time left until resolution\n~7 months (from June 2, 2026 to January 1, 2027)\n\n## (b) Status quo outcome if nothing changes\nThe ICJ case would likely remain unresolved by the deadline. ICJ cases typically take years to complete, and this case is still in early-to-middle stages of proceedings.\n\n## (c) Scenario for NO outcome\n- The ICJ does not issue a final judgment on the merits before January 1, 2027 (most likely scenario)\n- The case continues through normal deliberative processes, with a ruling expected in 2027-2028 or later\n- Even if the ICJ issues preliminary rulings or orders, these would not constitute a final \"finding\" of guilt on the merits\n- The court prioritizes thorough legal analysis over speed\n\n## (d) Scenario for YES outcome\n- The ICJ dramatically accelerates proceedings and issues a final judgment on the merits within 7 months\n- This judgment finds Israel violated the Genocide Convention\n- This would require an unprecedented expedited process for an ICJ case of this complexity and geopolitical significance\n\n## (e) Base rate \u2014 how often do similar events occur?\n\n**ICJ case timelines:**\n- Average ICJ case duration: 4-7 years from filing to judgment\n- South Africa filed in December 2023, making the case ~30 months old as of June 2026\n- Preliminary objections phase typically precedes merits judgment\n- Cases with high geopolitical stakes (like this one) tend to move slower, not faster, due to careful deliberation\n\n**Historical precedent:**\n- The Nicaragua v. United States case (filed 1984, judgment 1986): ~2 years - exceptionally fast\n- Most comparable cases take 5+ years\n- The ICJ has no incentive to rush a decision of this magnitude and political sensitivity\n\n## (f) How current data/news moves me from base rate\n\n**What I need to assess but don't have complete current information on:**\n- Current status of proceedings (preliminary objections, merits phase?)\n- Any recent ICJ rulings indicating timeline acceleration\n- Whether the ICJ has indicated when judgment might be expected\n\n**General considerations:**\n- ICJ cases of this complexity and political sensitivity typically do NOT accelerate\n- The court's credibility depends on appearing independent and thorough, not rushed\n- 7 months from June 2026 to January 2027 is an extremely tight timeframe for a final merits judgment\n- Even if preliminary objections were resolved by mid-2026, issuing a final judgment within ~6 months would be extraordinary\n\n## (g) Community prediction and divergence explanation\n\nI don't have access to community forecasting data on this specific question, but I can note that informed observers familiar with ICJ processes would likely have low expectations for a judgment by early 2027. The structural realities of international court proceedings create strong downward pressure on this probability.\n\n---\n\n## Probability Reasoning:\n\n**Against YES (7 months to judgment):**\n- Only 1 ICJ case in modern history (Nicaragua v. US) completed in ~2 years, and that's much faster than typical\n- This case involves complex factual questions about intent and genocide definition\n- Preliminary phases likely still ongoing or just completing\n- ICJ would face reputational damage from appearing to rush such a sensitive judgment\n- Both parties have strong incentives to present extensive documentation\n- Legal complexity of genocide determination is high\n\n**For YES:**\n- The case has been ongoing for ~2.5 years already (some procedural work complete)\n- High international attention might create some pressure for resolution\n- The ICJ could theoretically issue a merits judgment if preliminary issues are resolved\n\n**Mathematical anchor:**\n- If average case is 5+ years and this case is ~2.5 years in, only ~1.5 years of typical work remain (meaning judgment around late 2027 or 2028)\n- For judgment by January 1, 2027 would require completing all remaining work in 7 months\n- This is roughly 3-4x faster than typical ICJ proceedings\n- Historical precedent (Nicaragua case) suggests even the fastest cases take ~2 years minimum\n- Probability of such extreme acceleration: ~2-5%\n\n**Calibration check:** Given the extreme recency of the deadline relative to typical ICJ timelines, and the high complexity of this case, confidence below 5% is warranted.\n\n**Probability: 3%**",
    "status": "success"
  },
  "q_35765": {
    "question_id": 35765,
    "question_text": "Will a federal judge be impeached by Republican Representatives in a partisan vote before January 3, 2027?",
    "probability": 0.04,
    "reasoning": "# Analysis: Federal Judge Impeachment by Republican-Partisan Vote Before Jan 3, 2027\n\n## (a) Time left until resolution\n~7 months (from June 2, 2026 to January 3, 2027)\n\n## (b) Status quo outcome if nothing changes\nNo impeachment occurs. The current political environment, despite Trump's March 2025 call for Judge Boasberg's impeachment, has not resulted in any formal impeachment effort. The institutional resistance from Chief Justice Roberts and the general rarity of judge impeachment suggests the status quo continues.\n\n## (c) Scenario for NO outcome\n- The House Republican majority does not pursue impeachment of any federal judge\n- Even if judicial decisions anger Republican leadership, institutional norms and fear of precedent-setting hold\n- Democratic representatives either abstain or sufficient numbers vote \"no\" to prevent a partisan supermajority vote\n- The 7-month window is too short for sustained political pressure to overcome institutional inertia\n- Senate conviction is unlikely anyway (requiring 2/3), making House impeachment politically costly\n\n## (d) Scenario for YES outcome\n- A federal judge makes a high-profile ruling that enrages Trump and Republican leadership (e.g., on immigration, election law, or Trump-related cases)\n- House Republicans, emboldened by Trump's endorsement, formally introduce and pass an impeachment resolution\n- The vote follows partisan lines with >50% of Republicans voting yes and <50% of Democrats voting yes\n- This could occur if a controversial ruling provides political cover to justify impeachment as something other than purely partisan retaliation\n\n## (e) Base rate \u2014 how often do similar events occur?\n\n**Historical context on federal judge impeachment:**\n- Only 8 federal judges have ever been impeached in U.S. history\n- Only 1 has been convicted and removed (Judge Samuel Chase in 1805, though not actually removed)\n- Actually removed: None in modern era (since 1805)\n- Most recent impeachment: Judge Harry Claiborne (1986) - convicted but not removed\n- Average: ~1 impeachment per 25-30 years across all judges combined\n\n**Partisan impeachment of judges specifically:**\n- This is virtually unprecedented in modern American history\n- Judge Claiborne (1986) was impeached on tax charges, with some bipartisan support\n- The modern norm is that impeachment is not used for policy disagreements\n\n**Base rate for this specific question:** ~2-5% over any given 7-month period, given the extreme rarity and the institutional resistance demonstrated by Chief Justice Roberts' statement.\n\n## (f) How current data/news moves you from base rate\n\n**Factors pushing toward YES:**\n- Trump's explicit March 2025 call for Boasberg's impeachment shows willingness to pursue this\n- Republicans control the House (as of question creation context)\n- The Trump administration is actively seeking ideological loyalty from judges\n- Immigration and election-related cases remain contentious areas where judicial decisions could inflame Republicans\n- 7 months is a meaningful window for escalation\n\n**Factors pushing toward NO:**\n- Chief Justice Roberts' public pushback against using impeachment for judicial decisions is highly significant\n- No actual impeachment resolution has been introduced despite Trump's March 2025 call\n- This suggests Republican leadership recognizes political/institutional costs\n- Even Trump-aligned House members have not pursued this despite the public call\n- The resolution requires a partisan vote pattern (>50% R yes, <50% D yes), which is the most restrictive interpretation\n- Historical precedent strongly discourages this\n- Senate conviction is nearly impossible (requires 2/3), making House impeachment a performative gesture with costs\n- Federal judges have significant institutional protection\n- Boasberg ruling has not triggered actual impeachment proceedings despite months passing\n\n**Recent trajectory:** The fact that Trump called for impeachment in March 2025 and no resolution emerged by June 2026 (15 months later) is strong evidence that institutional constraints are holding.\n\n## (g) Community prediction comparison\n\nI don't have explicit community prediction data, but the Bright Line Watch framing (a nonpartisan watchdog) and the careful resolution language suggest this is tracking a concerning but low-probability scenario. The resolution criteria requiring a \"partisan vote\" (fewer than half of Democrats voting yes) is designed to capture the most egregious case\u2014a purely partisan impeachment.\n\nMy probability should be lower than base rates might suggest because:\n- 15 months have already passed since Trump's explicit call with no action\n- Institutional resistance is demonstrably strong\n- The 7-month remaining window is short\n- The Senate conviction barrier makes this largely symbolic\n\n## Probability Assessment\n\nStarting from a base rate of ~3% for any 7-month period with these rare events, I adjust downward because:\n- The recent inaction (despite Trump's call) is strong negative evidence (-40% adjustment)\n- Institutional resistance is explicit and high (-20% adjustment)\n- The short remaining timeframe (-10% adjustment)\n- But Trump's explicit March 2025 call and control of the House keeps this above zero (+15% adjustment)\n\nThe resolution criteria requiring a partisan vote pattern is the most restrictive form, which further reduces probability.\n\n**Probability: 4%**",
    "status": "success"
  },
