    "probability": 0.78,
    "reasoning": "# Analysis: Will Mike Johnson Remain Speaker Until January 3, 2027?\n\n## (a) Time Left Until Resolution\nFrom June 2, 2026 to January 3, 2027 = approximately 7 months\n\n## (b) Status Quo Outcome If Nothing Changes\nMike Johnson remains Speaker and completes his tenure through the end of the 119th Congress. The baseline assumption is continuity.\n\n## (c) Scenario for NO Outcome\n- A motion to vacate is filed and succeeds (like McCarthy in October 2023)\n- Johnson voluntarily resigns from the speakership before January 3, 2027\n- Johnson is removed through some extraordinary constitutional process\n- Republicans collectively lose confidence and force a speakership election with Johnson losing\n\nThe Politico and Axios reporting from December 2025 indicated significant internal pressure, delayed NDAA bills, and GOP infighting. The \"mini-preview\" suggested ongoing turmoil ahead.\n\n## (d) Scenario for YES Outcome\n- Johnson navigates the remaining 7 months of the 119th Congress\n- The NDAA and other must-pass legislation passes despite intraparty friction\n- Public criticism moderates once bills pass\n- No motion to vacate achieves traction\n- Institutional inertia prevails: removing a Speaker mid-Congress is disruptive\n\n## (e) Base Rate \u2014 How Often Do Similar Events Occur?\n\n**Historical precedent for Speaker removal/resignation:**\n- Kevin McCarthy: Removed via motion to vacate (October 2023) - lasted 9 months as Speaker\n- Paul Ryan: Completed full terms voluntarily\n- John Boehner: Resigned voluntarily mid-Congress (2015) after facing similar revolts\n- Before McCarthy (in modern era): Speakers typically serve full terms once elected\n\nIn the 119th Congress specifically:\n- Johnson was re-elected Speaker in January 2025 with a similar slim 219-215 majority\n- He has already survived ~5 months (January-June 2026) despite reported pressure\n- Base rate for a Speaker surviving their full term once past the halfway mark: ~75-80%\n\nHowever, the McCarthy precedent (9 months) and Boehner precedent (voluntary resignation under pressure) suggest vulnerability with thin majorities.\n\n## (f) How Current Data/News Moves Me From Base Rate\n\n**Key update: Today is June 2, 2026** - This is crucial context:\n\nThe question references December 2025 reporting as current at that time. We are now 6 months past those warnings. The fact that:\n1. Johnson has survived from December 2025 through June 2026 despite reported turmoil\n2. No motion to vacate was filed in the intervening 6 months\n3. The NDAA and other bills appear to have passed (or Johnson managed them)\n4. Only 7 months remain until resolution\n\n**This significantly increases the YES probability.** Johnson has already navigated the most dangerous period identified in the December 2025 reporting. The trajectory from December's crisis to June's stability suggests:\n- The immediate pressure has passed\n- His leadership survived the anticipated test cases\n- Institutional inertia strongly favors completion now\n\n**Risk factors remaining:**\n- Unexpected crises could emerge in the final 7 months\n- Government funding battles ahead\n- Health care fights mentioned in the reporting\n- Midterm elections dynamics (though these occur in 2026, creating post-election dynamics for remainder of 119th Congress)\n\nHowever, these are generic risks, not specific imminent threats.\n\n## (g) Community Prediction Divergence\n\nWithout access to current prediction markets, I cannot directly compare. However, given:\n- The 6-month track record of survival past the December crisis point\n- Only 7 months remaining (short timeframe for significant political realignments)\n- McCarthy lasted 9 months before removal (Johnson is already past that mark)\n- The absence of current motions to vacate\n\nI would expect community forecasters to be pricing this higher now (June 2026) than they would have in December 2025. If any community estimate from December 2025 was ~40-50%, I would expect June 2026 estimates to be ~65-75%.\n\n## Reasoning Summary\n\n**Factors supporting YES (higher probability):**\n- Johnson has already survived 6 months past the crisis point identified in December 2025\n- No motion to vacate emerged during the most volatile period\n- Only 7 months remain - limited time for new crises to develop\n- McCarthy lasted 9 months before removal; Johnson is past that\n- Institutional pressure to avoid another Speaker crisis is strong\n- Completing one's term is the modal outcome for Speakers\n\n**Factors supporting NO (lower probability):**\n- Slim 219-215 majority remains inherently fragile\n- Unresolved fights over healthcare, funding remain on agenda\n- Historical precedent: McCarthy and Boehner both faced successful/voluntary exits under similar pressure\n- \"Escalating public criticism\" pattern mirrors pre-McCarthy dynamics\n- Unknown unknowns in final 7 months\n\n**Calibration adjustment:**\nBase rate for Speaker completing term when past midpoint with thin majority: ~75-80%\nAdjustment for Johnson's 6-month survival past crisis: +8-10 percentage points\nAdjustment for remaining timeframe being short: +3-5 percentage points\nConservative discount for thin majority and historical volatility: -5 percentage points\n\n**Probability: 78%**",
