    "reasoning": "# Analysis: Will Elon Musk Be Removed as Tesla CEO Before 2027?\n\n## (a) Time left until resolution\nApproximately 7 months remain until January 1, 2027 (from June 2, 2026).\n\n## (b) Status quo outcome if nothing changes\nElon Musk remains Tesla CEO through the resolution date. This is the baseline assumption given that:\n- Musk has been Tesla CEO since 2008 (18 years)\n- He has weathered numerous controversies, regulatory challenges, and board pressures\n- As of the May 2025 reporting, despite board succession planning, both Musk and the board publicly reaffirmed confidence in his leadership\n- No current evidence suggests imminent removal\n\n## (c) Scenario for NO outcome (Musk remains CEO)\n- Musk continues current trajectory with no material change in board dynamics or his role\n- Any succession planning remains contingency/future-focused rather than imminent\n- Market conditions, Tesla performance, or governance issues don't escalate sufficiently to force removal\n- Personal circumstances remain stable (no incapacity, no unexpected resignation)\n\n## (d) Scenario for YES outcome (Musk removed before Jan 1, 2027)\n- Board escalates concerns about: governance issues, time allocation (Musk's involvement with X/Twitter), regulatory compliance, or strategic disagreements\n- Major Tesla performance decline triggers shareholder/board action\n- Significant legal/regulatory crisis forces removal\n- Personal health crisis or incapacity\n- Musk voluntarily resigns under pressure\n- Tesla undergoes restructuring that changes executive titles/structure\n\n## (e) Base rate \u2014 how often do similar events occur?\n\n**Comparable CEO departures:**\n- S&P 500 CEO turnover: ~13-15% annually (fairly high rate)\n- However, \"forced departure\" vs. voluntary: ~40-50% of departures are forced\n- Fortune 500 CEOs with founder/major shareholder status: Much lower removal rates (~2-5% annually) due to control and alignment\n- Elon Musk's specific position: Founder, largest shareholder (~13%), visionary leader = exceptionally difficult to remove against his will\n\n**Base rate for founder-CEOs remaining in role over 7-month period:**\n- ~97-98% remain (inverse of ~2-3% annual forced removal rate, compressed to 7 months)\n\n## (f) How current data/news moves you from base rate\n\n**Factors pushing toward YES (removal):**\n- May 2025 WSJ report of board actively searching for successors is significant signal\n- Board concern about CEO focus/time allocation is credible governance issue\n- Tesla faces increasing regulatory scrutiny globally\n- Recent stock volatility and competitive pressures (EV market)\n- Board composition may have independent-minded members (Robyn Denholm as chair)\n\n**Factors pushing toward NO (remaining):**\n- Both Musk and board immediately and forcefully denied succession planning\n- Musk owns ~13% and has deep control through voting agreements\n- His removal would require either: (a) voluntary resignation, or (b) board supermajority vote against a founder-CEO with major shareholdings\u2014extremely difficult\n- 7 months is a very short window for governance change to escalate to removal\n- No current crisis-level event reported\n- Historical pattern: Musk has survived far more serious controversies (SEC settlements, Twitter acquisition, etc.)\n\n**Institutional inertia weighs heavily:** Removing a founder-CEO with significant shareholdings requires extraordinary circumstances. The fact that the board felt compelled to publicly deny succession planning suggests they wanted to quell removal speculation\u2014implying it's not currently probable.\n\n## (g) Community prediction comparison\nI don't have access to current Metaculus community predictions for this question, but based on typical forecasting on similar CEO departure questions:\n- Most forecasters would likely estimate 5-15% for a 7-month window\n- The base rate alone (2-3% annually compressed to 7 months \u2248 1.2-1.75%) would be the anchor\n- The