    "reasoning": "# Analysis: Will Nvidia's stock close below $100 in 2026?\n\n## (a) Time left until resolution\nWe are currently at June 2, 2026. The question resolves at the end of 2026 (December 31, 2026). That leaves approximately 7 months of trading days remaining.\n\n## (b) Status quo outcome if nothing changes\nNvidia closed at $182.41 on December 5, 2025. If business conditions remain stable and the company continues executing on strong demand for Blackwell chips, the stock would likely trade in the $150-200+ range through 2026, given:\n- Continued dominance in AI chip market (70-95% share)\n- Sustained demand exceeding supply through H1 2026\n- Strong capital expenditure commitments from major tech customers\n- No major supply chain disruptions\n\nUnder status quo, the stock stays well above $100.\n\n## (c) Scenario for NO outcome\nNvidia avoids closing below $100 if:\n- AI capex spending continues at current or elevated levels\n- Blackwell supply continues to be constrained relative to demand\n- Google TPU competition remains niche and doesn't materially erode market share\n- China restrictions don't collapse revenue materially (China already represented modest % of revenues)\n- No major macro recession/tech downturn occurs\n- No catastrophic execution failures or geopolitical escalations\n\nThis is the base case scenario.\n\n## (d) Scenario for YES outcome\nNvidia closes below $100 if ONE OR MORE of these occur:\n1. **Severe recession/tech downturn**: Market-wide 40-50% correction hitting high-growth tech stocks\n2. **AI capex cliff**: Major customers suddenly reduce spending on GPU infrastructure\n3. **Competitive displacement**: Google TPUs, AMD, or other alternatives rapidly gain material share\n4. **Regulatory/geopolitical crisis**: Major escalation in US-China tensions affecting global supply chains\n5. **Business failure**: Demand collapses faster than expected, or major execution problems\n6. **Valuation collapse**: Stock re-rates down due to margin compression or growth slowdown\n\nA 45% decline from $182.41 to below $100 would require one of these major negative catalysts.\n\n## (e) Base rate \u2014 how often do similar events occur?\n\nLooking at Nvidia's 26-year history (per MacroTrends data):\n- Nvidia has experienced multiple significant drawdowns exceeding 50% in its history\n- The 2022-2023 bear market saw Nvidia drop from $300+ to lows around $100-120 range\n- During the dot-com crash and 2008 financial crisis, tech stocks fell 70-90%\n- However, 2025 ended with Nvidia at elevated levels after strong 2024-2025 run\n\n**Base rate context**: In any given year, a high-growth mega-cap tech stock has roughly:\n- 5-15% chance of a 40%+ decline in a typical year\n- Higher probability (~20-30%) in recession years\n- Lower probability (~5-10%) in strong growth years\n\nFor a mega-cap stock at near all-time valuations, a 45% decline in a 7-month window is meaningful but not unprecedented.\n\n**Base rate estimate: ~10-15% for a major tech stock in normal market conditions**\n\n## (f) How current data/news moves you from base rate\n\n**Factors pushing toward YES (higher probability):**\n- Stock is at elevated levels ($182) after strong run, potentially vulnerable to profit-taking\n- China restrictions eliminate growth avenue (though modest % of revenue)\n- Google TPU competition is real and improving\n- 7 months remaining = significant time window for negative catalysts\n- Valuation appears stretched by some metrics after 36% YTD 2025 rally\n- Macro environment uncertain heading into H2 2026\n\n**Factors pushing toward NO (lower probability):**\n- Strong execution fundamentals: selling all Blackwell chips produced\n- Supply constraints expected to persist through FY2026\n- Massive TAM expansion with AI infrastructure buildout still in early innings\n- Major tech customers (MSFT, AMZN, GOOG, META) all deeply committed to AI capex\n- Nvidia's competitive moat remains formidable despite TPU progress\n- China already a small % of revenue due to prior export restrictions\n- Business momentum is strong heading into H2 2026\n\n**Net adjustment**: The strong fundamentals and supply-constrained situation argue against a major collapse. However, the 7-month window and potential for unexpected negative catalysts (macro downturn, geopolitical escalation, competitive acceleration) provide meaningful tail risk.\n\nThe current data suggests the base rate should be adjusted downward somewhat from the historical 10-15% for a mega-cap in normal times, given Nvidia's strong positioning. However, the question's 45% move requirement and extended timeframe prevent moving too far down.\n\n## (g) Community prediction comparison\n\nI don't have access to current community forecasts on this specific question, but I would expect most forecasters would estimate this at relatively low probability (5-20%), given:\n- Nvidia's strong current position\n- Supply constraints supporting pricing power\n- AI demand still in growth phase\n- Recent strong performance reducing likelihood of deep bearish calls\n\nIf community estimates this at 5-10%, I might diverge slightly higher (to 12-16%) to account for tail risks and the 7-month window, but the direction of divergence would be minor.\n\n## Final Reasoning\n\nTo reach below $100 requires either:\n1. A macro/tech downturn (market-wide 40%+ decline) - ~15% probability\n2. Nvidia-specific collapse (competitive loss, demand cliff, execution failure) - ~8% probability\n3. Combination of moderate negative factors - ~5% probability\n\nThese aren't perfectly independent but have meaningful overlap.\n\nThe question has already resolved 6 months into 2026, which increases the probability somewhat since we can observe actual performance through mid-year. The fact that we're being asked this in early June suggests the stock may have declined from $182 (or possibly rallied further). Without current price data provided, I must assume the question is being asked in genuine uncertainty about whether $100 will be touched.\n\nGiven:\n- 7 months of remaining trading days (high number for a tail event)\n- Strong fundamentals but elevated valuation\n- Multiple potential negative catalysts\n- Historical precedent for tech drawdowns\n- Supply constraints and demand strength supporting floor\n\n**Probability: 14%**",
